%pyspark

from pyspark.sql import functions as F
from pyspark.sql import Window

history = history.withColumn("polled_time", history["polled_time"].cast("timestamp"))
history = history.withColumn("update_time", history["update_time"].cast("timestamp"))
history = history.withColumn("polled_time_hr", F.hour("polled_time"))
history = history.withColumn("polled_time_mn", F.minute("polled_time"))
history = history.withColumn("polled_time_seg", history["polled_time_hr"] + history["polled_time_mn"] / 60)
history = history.withColumn("polled_time_ampk", history["polled_time_seg"].between(7.5, 10).cast("integer"))
history = history.withColumn("polled_time_pmpk", history["polled_time_seg"].between(16, 19).cast("integer"))
history = history.withColumn("polled_time_dayofweek", F.date_format("polled_time", "u"))
history = history.withColumn("polled_time_weekday", (history["polled_time_dayofweek"] < 6).cast("integer"))


# this is a workaround due to unexpected results from the Window functionality
sqlContext.sql("drop table bikepoint.historyTemp")
history.write.saveAsTable("bikepoint.historyTemp")


# calculate number of spaces in prior period (lag 1)
history = sqlContext.sql("""select *, 
max(spaces) over(partition by id order by polled_time rows between 2 preceding and 1 preceding) as spaces_lag1,
max(spaces) over(partition by id order by polled_time rows between 3 preceding and 2 preceding) as spaces_lag2,
max(spaces) over(partition by id order by polled_time rows between 4 preceding and 3 preceding) as spaces_lag3
from bikepoint.historyTemp""")

history = history.dropna()

history.show(20)

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark

pols = fiona.open("/home/slbm/london-gis/ESRI/London_Borough_Excluding_MHW.shp")

def locationData(lat, lon):
    CHX_E = 530196
    CHX_N = 180510
    easting, northing = convert_bng(lon, lat)
    
    chxDist = math.sqrt((easting[0] - CHX_E)**2+(northing[0] - CHX_N)**2)
    
    p = Point(easting[0], northing[0])

    for pol in pols:
        s = shape(pol["geometry"])
        if s.contains(p):
            return pol["properties"]["NAME"], 1 if pol["properties"]["ONS_INNER"] == "T" else 0, easting[0], northing[0], chxDist
    return "", 0, 0, 0, 0

# test IBM Southbank
# print locationData(51.507462, -0.11261980)

# test bikepoint_134 -> wapping high street
print locationData(51.504904, -0.06797)

%pyspark
# We can extract the London Borough boundaries by filtering on the AREA_CODE key
mp = MultiPolygon(
    [shape(pol["geometry"]) for pol in fiona.open("/home/slbm/london-gis/ESRI/London_Borough_Excluding_MHW.shp")])
    
# We can now do GIS-ish operations on each borough polygon!
# we could randomize this by dumping the polygons into a list and shuffling it
# or we could define a random colour using fc=np.random.rand(3,)
# available colour maps are here: http://wiki.scipy.org/Cookbook/Matplotlib/Show_colormaps
cm = plt.get_cmap('RdBu')
num_colours = len(mp)
 
fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
minx, miny, maxx, maxy = mp.bounds
w, h = maxx - minx, maxy - miny
ax.set_xlim(minx - 0.2 * w, maxx + 0.2 * w)
ax.set_ylim(miny - 0.2 * h, maxy + 0.2 * h)
ax.set_aspect(1)

patches = []
for idx, p in enumerate(mp):
    colour = cm(1. * idx / num_colours)
    patches.append(PolygonPatch(p, fc=colour, ec='#555555', alpha=1., zorder=1))
ax.add_collection(PatchCollection(patches, match_original=True))
ax.set_xticks([])
ax.set_yticks([])
plt.title("Shapefile polygons rendered using Shapely")
show(plt)
